We start by extracting the key numbers from the provided statements.

Step 1. Calculate Return on Equity (ROE)  
• Net Profit: 1,842,166.21 (from the income statement)  
• Owner’s Equity at the beginning (Paid‑in Capital + initial Retained Earnings): 28,000,000.00  
• Owner’s Equity at the end: 29,842,166.21  
→ Average Owner’s Equity = (28,000,000.00 + 29,842,166.21) / 2  
                = 57,842,166.21 / 2  
                ≈ 28,921,083.11  
→ ROE = (Net Profit / Average Owner’s Equity) × 100%  
    ≈ (1,842,166.21 / 28,921,083.11) × 100%  
    ≈ 0.0637 × 100%  
    ≈ 6.37%

Step 2. Calculate Debt to Asset Ratio  
• Total Liabilities = Total Assets – Total Owner’s Equity  
    = 30,858,088.75 – 29,842,166.21  
    = 1,015,922.54  
• Total Assets = 30,858,088.75  
→ Debt to Asset Ratio = Total Liabilities / Total Assets  
    ≈ 1,015,922.54 / 30,858,088.75  
    ≈ 0.0329  
Rounded, this is approximately 0.03.

Step 3. Calculate Gross Profit Margin  
• Gross Profit = 5,718,450.67  
• Total Revenue = 20,318,450.67  
→ Gross Profit Margin = (Gross Profit / Total Revenue) × 100%  
    ≈ (5,718,450.67 / 20,318,450.67) × 100%  
    ≈ 0.2813 × 100%  
    ≈ 28.13%

Thus, the final answers are:

{
  "solution": {
    "Return on Equity (ROE)": "6.37%",
    "Debt to Asset Ratio": "0.03",
    "Gross Profit Margin": "28.13%"
  }
}
